agment in the archeology of all these discursive strands. The task of the critic, now invited to pass through the discourses of philosophy, poetry, and religion beyond that of close reading, has never been harder—nor have we ever been more in need of it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322466140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329322340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823293223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823293223/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK